#### Quick Build
You can make a death knight quickly by following these suggestions. First, make Strength your highest ability score, followed by Charisma. Second, choose the **BACKGROUND**. Third, choose the **CANTRIP** and **CANTRIP** cantrips and the **RUNE** rune.

#### Optional Rule: Multiclassing
If your group uses the optional rule on multiclassing in the *Player's Handbook*, here's what you need to know if you choose death knight as one of your classes.

***Ability Score Minimum.*** As a multiclass character, you must have at least a Strength and Charisma score of 13 to take a level in this class, or to take a level in another class if you are already a death knight.

***Proficiencies Gained.*** If death knight isn't your initial class, here are the proficiencies you gain when you take your first level as a death knight: light armor, medium armor, simple weapons, martial weapons.

***Spell Slots.*** Add half your levels (rounded up) in the death knight class to the appropriate levels from other class to determine your available spell slots.

\columnbreak
## Class Features
As a death knight, you gain the following class features.

#### Hit Points
___
- **Hit Dice:** 1d12 per death knight level
- **Hit Points at 1st Level:** 12 + your Constitution modifier
- **Hit Points at Higher Levels:** 1d12 (or 7) + your Constitution modifier per death knight level

#### Proficiencies
___
- **Armor:** All armors, shields
- **Weapons:** Simple weapons, martial weapons
- **Tools:** None
___
- **Saving Throws:** Constitution, Charisma
- **Skills:** Choose two from Athletics, Deception, Intimidation, Investigation, Perception, and Stealth

#### Equipment
You start with the following equipment, in addition to the equipment granted by your background:
- *(a)* a martial weapon or *(b)* two shortswords
- *(a)* five javelins or *(b)* any simple weapon
- *(a)* scale mail or *(b)* chain mail
- *(a)* a dungeoneer's pack or *(b)* an explorer's pack
- A trinket from your past life

\pagebreakNum

<!-- <img src='https://www.gmbinder.com/images/0Juz7SO.png' style='position:absolute; top:800px; left:45px; width:350px; z-index:1' /> -->

### Dark Rebirth
*1st-level death knight feature*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

**[Lore text goes here.]**

Every death knight shares a number of physical traits: their eyes glow with a pale blue light, their body feels cool to the touch, and their voice gains a deep echo. Their emotions and memories from before they became a death knight are distant and dulled. They also gain an eternal hunger for causing suffering and death, an addiction that if not sated regularly will inevitably result in insanity.

___
As a death knight, you gain the following traits: 

***Undead Nature.*** Your creature type is undead, rather than humanoid. This renders you immune to certain spells, both beneficial and harmful, and makes you vulnerable to other spells and effects. See the Non-Humanoid Races sidebar on page **##** for more information.

You also gain the following traits:
- You are immune to non-magical poisons and diseases.
- You have advantage on death saving throws.
- You don't need to eat, drink, or breathe.
- You no longer age and will not die from old age.
- You don’t need to sleep, and magic can’t put you to sleep. You can finish a long rest in 4 hours if you spend those hours in an inactive, motionless state, during which you retain consciousness.

##### Death Knight Quirks
d6| |Quirks
--|-|--------
1 || Your body temperature becomes arctic, causing your breath to fog and the air around you to gain a deep chill.
2 || Your presence feels unnatural, causing others to feel uneasy near you and animals such as dogs to become hostile.
3 || You gain a taste for food typically consumed by lower undead, such as humanoid flesh, vermin, and insects.
4 || Your memory of your previous life is especially dulled. Alternatively, it is almost entirely intact.
5 || You become obsessed with one particular food, drink, or hobby that you liked in life but can no longer enjoy.
6 || You are a little too comfortable with death and violence and have no problems with desecrating corpses and graveyards.

\columnbreak

### Runic Magic
*1st-level death knight feature*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

**[DK Spellcasting Flavor Intro.]**

#### Cantrips
You know two cantrips of your choice from the death knight spell list. You learn additional death knight cantrips of your choice at higher levels, as shown in the Cantrips Known column of the Death Knight table.

#### Runeblade
You know how to inscribe magical runes onto a nonmagical weapon, transforming it into a runeblade—the source of your power. The ritual to do so takes 1 hour and consumes 50 gp worth of components. You can only have a single runeblade at a time. Bonding with a new weapon immediately breaks the bond with any previous runeblade.

Your weapon counts as magical for the purpose of overcoming resistance and immunity to nonmagical attacks and damage.

You can't be disarmed of your runeblade unless you are incapacitated. If it is on the same plane of existence as you, you can summon your runeblade as a bonus action on your turn, causing it to teleport instantly to your hand. **[TBH, I don't like this part. I'd rather you instinctually know which direction it is.]**

You produce your death knight rune effects through your runeblade. You must have your runeblade within 5 feet of you when using an ability that requires runic power.

#### Runes
Your runeblade is inscribed with a number of runes, each of which embodies a specific concept, such as Anger, Cruelty, or Vengeance. The number of runes inscribed on your runeblade is shown on the Inscribed Runes column of the Death Knight table. When you gain a level in this class, you can replace one rune you know with a different one of your choice.

#### Runic Power
You have a reservoir of energy drawn from your runes that can be used to power certain magical powers. This energy is represented by runic power. Each rune describes effects you can create with it by spending a certain amount of runic power.

The amount of runic power you have is based on your death knight level, as shown in the Runic Power column of the Death Knight table. The number shown for your level is your maximum runic power. Your runic power total returns to its maximum when you finish a short or long rest. The amount of runic power you have can't go below 0 or over your maximum.

<!--
#### Power Limit
Though you have access to a potent amount of runic power, it takes training and practice to channel that energy. There is a limit on the amount of runic power you can spend to activate a rune. The limit is based on your death knight level, as shown in the Power Limit column of the Death Knight table. For example, as a 5th-level death knight, you can spend no more than 3 runic power on a rune each time you use it, no matter how much runic power you have.
-->

#### Spellcasting Ability
Some rune abilities replicate spells or require an attack roll or saving throw. Charisma is your spellcasting ability, so you use your Charisma whenever a spell refers to your spellcasting ability. In addition, you use your Charisma modifier when setting the saving throw DC for a death knight spell you cast or ability your use and when making an attack roll with one.

<div style="text-align: Center">

**Spell save DC** = 8 + your proficiency bonus + <br> your Charisma modifier

**Spell attack modifier** = your proficiency bonus + <br> your Charisma modifier
</div>

\pagebreakNum

### Fighting Style
*2nd-level death knight feature*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You adopt a particular style of fighting as your specialty. Choose one of the following options. You can't take a Fighting Style option more than once, even if you later get to choose again.

#### Defense
While you are wearing armor, you gain a +1 bonus to AC.

#### Dueling
When you are wielding a melee weapon in one hand and no other weapons, you gain a +2 bonus to damage rolls with that weapon.

#### Great Weapon Fighting
When you roll a 1 or 2 on a damage die for an attack you make with a melee weapon that you are wielding with two hands, you can reroll the die and must use the new roll, even if the new roll is a 1 or a 2. The weapon must have the two-handed or versatile property for you to gain this benefit.

#### Profane Warrior
You learn an additional two cantrips of your choice from the death knight spell list.

#### Two-Weapon Fighting
When you engage in two-weapon fighting, you can add your ability modifier to the damage of the second attack.

> #### Optional Class Features
> See Tasha's Cauldron of Everything, Pg. 41 for additional Fighting Styles. The Interception, Superior Technique, and Unarmed Fighting styles are appropriate choices for this class.

<div style='margin-top:35px;'></div>

\columnbreak

### Rune Tap
*2nd-level death knight feature*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You can invoke a rune to gain one of a following effects:
- ***Rune Tap.*** You can expend a rune as a bonus action to regain hit points equal to 1d12 + your death knight level.
- **Death Coil?**
- **Combine the above two, healing yourself with Death Coil, firing it as a beam, or using it as a smite?**
- **Death Grip?**

### UNKNOWN-3
*3rd-level death knight feature*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You are now able to turn magical weapons into a runeblade. 

You can also inscribe a rune onto a second weapon, turning it into a lesser runeblade. As long as you are wielding your primary runeblade, this lesser runeblade counts as a magical weapon and you cannot be disarmed of it unless incapacitated. You can summon both weapons to your hands as part of the same bonus action.

### Knighthood
*3rd-level death knight feature* 
<div style='margin-top:-4px'></div>

You choose a path of knighthood to follow, focusing on a single rune's concept. You can choose to become a Knight of Blood, Knight of Frost, or Knight of the Unholy. Your choice of knighthood provides features at 3rd level and again at 7th, 10th, and 15th level.

#### Knight Rune
Each Knighthood has an associated rune. You inscribe this rune onto your runeblade when you select your Knighthood path and it does not count against the number of runes you have inscribed. If you already have this rune, you can inscribe a different rune of your choice.

### Ability Score Improvement
*4th-level death knight feature*
<div style='margin-top:-4px'></div>

When you reach 4th level, and again at 8th, 12th, 16th, and 19th level, you can increase one ability score of your choice by 2, or you can increase two ability scores of your choice by 1. As normal, you can't increase an ability score above 20 using this feature.

#### Deathly Versatility (Optional)
Whenever you reach a level in this class that grants the Ability Score Improvement feature, you can do one of the following, representing a change of focus:
- Replace a fighting style you know with another fighting style available to death knights.
- Replace one cantrip you learned from this class' Runic Magic feature with another cantrip from the death knight spell list.

### Extra Attack
*5th-level death knight feature*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You can attack twice, instead of once, whenever you take the Attack action on your turn.

\pagebreakNum

